description: I've a pretty distinctive bird call making a lot of noise for himself recently. If you can make sense of the recording (my first attempt to add a sound observation), I'd be keen to know what it is please.
Looks like our resident Tui is back. I've also made an audio track but the camera auto focus spoiled it for a bit.
Tui enjoying the nectar from the flax behind our house.
The second and third recording show the noise pollution they have to contend with.

In the first sound file it emits a dit-dit sounds which is actually very loud, and I couldn't amplify the overall sound track without forcing that to be clipped (and hence distorted) - so the other parts of the call are somewhat quieter than normal.  The second sound file is it flying away.
Feeding from Darwins Barberry flowers and singing from nearby trees.
Sitting on top of a dead tree fern inside the Karori sanctuary.

The large Puriri tree near our house is attracting the Tuis. This one was sounding very melodious and I was able to record his song though some was in too high a register for me to hear.

The leaves you can see in the foreground are from a Karaka which is growing up through one side of the Puriri.

The recordings were taken using my camera and extracted using Audacity. There is background noise from a small aircraft as well as doves calling. At times I could see the singing movements but could hear no sound as it was in a very high register.

tag_list: Svrh
description:
From tree above bird bath, after at least three tui had been bathing briefly throughout the afternoon. EDIT.. prior to and after  this observation, ie the social background to this vocalization: there is a group of young tui in these trees frequently throughout recent few weeks. They perch on an unused  rail, under trees between houses, a couple of metres above a rainwater tank with a dish of water on top of it. They look up, down and to both sides, repeatedly, before flying down to the bird bath (2m above ground, under trees to about 6mH with houses on either side). While perched on the rail preparing to take the plunge, if another perches on the same rail the first one threatens it with wide-open beaks, chases it off, then returns and takes the plunge. 

However, This observation is of a relaxed vocalization from a tui hidden among higher tree foliage, similar to the sounds made when an identifiable tui has achieved its bath.
Link to Video taken in kawakawa tree to right within a minute of this still shot, but it could be a different tui as there were at least three around the bath at the time.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vLB9LkRv1rI&feature=youtu.be

description:
I observed this bird singing in a tree above me. I could see that it was singing but could only hear an occasional note and think that it was using mainly very high register notes beyond the range of human hearing. 

I have now extracted the audio track from the video I took with my cellphone and after amplifying the sound in Audacity I am now able to hear much of the very high-pitched song of the Tui, with ambient sounds, mainly of my flock of laying hens that had followed me.

Lovely to get some nice views of one of the Banks Peninsula Tui!
At one point one flew past me, only about 30cm from my head!
Multiple birds
